  "observation": "Brainstorm triggered by plateau. 4 proposals generated.",
  "suggestion": "The plateau is not a fitness maximum — it is a **selection stagnation**. Organisms have fully exploited the current reward topology. No new selective pressure exists to discriminate among similar designs. Parameter tuning redistributes the same fitness; structural change introduces NEW dimensions that force agents into unexplored phenotype space. Predation creates asymmetric pressure; development creates temporal pressure; environment gradients create spatial pressure. All three break the symmetry that led to plateau.; [medium] Introduce predator-prey asymmetry: create two organism classes with fundamentally different roles. Prey optimize for evasion/reproduction; predators optimize for hunting efficiency. Organisms can only 'see' or interact with the other class within a range. World spawn ratio is dynamic (predators increase if prey abundant, vice versa). — Current system likely optimizes single-organism survival in isolation. Predation creates continuous adaptive pressure — an evolutionary arms race. Prey discover new beauty through evasion patterns; predators through hunting intelligence. This breaks symmetry and unlocks selection for traits that only matter under threat.; [hard] Add developmental stages: organisms now grow through discrete phases (juvenile → adult → reproductive) with different cell type access and action constraints at each stage. Growth transitions are triggered by resource accumulation or time. Beauty scoring includes phase-transition elegance (smooth morphing, efficient pacing). — Currently organisms are born fully-formed and static. Development adds a temporal dimension to morphology. Organisms must balance juvenile efficiency, adult complexity, and reproductive success across a lifecycle. New beauty emerges in growth patterns. Decision function must reason about developmental state, fundamentally altering selection.; [medium] Introduce spatial environmental gradients with mobile resources: instead of uniform resource availability, create moving chemical/nutrient plumes that drift with world currents. Organisms gain a new sensory action (chemotaxis direction) that couples to movement. Beauty metric includes efficient resource-tracking behavior. — Plateau suggests organisms have optimized for static environment. Introducing mobile resources forces discovery of new navigation/sensing strategies. Organisms must evolve prediction and long-range planning. Current decision function (likely myopic, local-only) becomes a bottleneck — agents discover emergent long-horizon strategies. New beauty emerges in pursuit and evasion patterns.",
